        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The number of spectral resolution elements per line width (4.5) is enough to resolve the assumed HCN line width per individual beam.

The width of spectral window is also wide enough to do continuum subtraction of the emission lines and cover the line broadening due to galaxy rotation.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose 1 arcsec resolution observation so that we can resolve molecular gas associations and match the resolution of other optical and radio data, but still keeping a reasonable amount of integration time. The largest angular resolution is based on CO(2-1) observation, which show a disk-like structure of molecular gas extending 22 arcsec in diameter. In this respect, we request a 22" x 22" rectangular grid of mosaic observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on previous observations of 12CO(2-1), HCN(1-0)/CO(2-1) line ratio from Krips et al. (2010), and HCN(3-2)/HCN(1-0) line ratio from Krips et al. (2008), we estimate HCN(3-2) has flux density of 5.7 mJy in 1 arcsec resolution. Therefore, we request 2.4 hours of observing time to reach S/N of 5 for HCN(3-2) observation.

We pick spectral resolution of 4.4 km/s, which will resolve the line width if the HCN line width is comparable to the 12CO(2-1) linewidth (~20 km/s; Utomo et al. 2015). This is the resolved line width in each individual beam, not the total.

In the lower side-band, we also request dust continuum observation at 250 GHz. By using the assumption that the dust has temperature of 15 K, we estimate flux sensitivity of 0.427 mJy for 1 arcsec resolution, 7.813 MHz resolution, and 2.4 hours of observing time. This sensitivity equivalent to H2 column density of 1.5 x 10^22 cm^-2 or 345 Solar mass per square parsec. Based on 12CO(2-1) observations, Utomo et al. (2015) estimate gas surface density of ~ 1000 Solar mass per square parsec, so the dust continuum will likely be detected at 3-sigma level.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We do not need ACA to cover the largest angular scale of the source because we have selected mosaic observation with rectangular grid to cover all structures of the source.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ACA_SETUP</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
