    <prp:abstract>Recent observations show that early-type galaxies (ETGs) can contain cold gas, which is the reservoir of star formation. Nevertheless, evidence suggests that ETGs also have lower star formation efficiencies than late-type galaxies (LTGs). The suppression of star formation in ETGs is a puzzling question. In order to address this problem, we need a direct measurement of the dense gas tracers at high resolution and compare it directly to equally high resolution observation of the star formation rates (SFR) of ETG. Also, observations of dust continuum would give us a robust measurement of the molecular gas mass in ETGs, independent of the CO-to-H2 conversion factor. Here, we propose to observe HCN, HCO+, and dust continuum to reveal the structure and properties of dense gas and dust in the central region of NGC 4526. We will combine this observation with UV, CO, and radio continuum data, that we already have in hand, and H-alpha map from the Hubble Space Telescope (Cycle 23) to better understand why cold gas in ETGs does not form stars as in LTGs.</prp:abstract>
